Quick Start Guide

First you need to install python. Grab a copy of Anaconda from here: https://www.continuum.io/downloads and install it. Anaconda is a distribution of python that contains a lot of the most used and useful packages. (Anaconda, python.. see what they did there?)
Next up, you'll need the bottlenose package-
The easiest way to download this is to type in this command in the command line - pip install bottlenose
If you see an error, then do the following-

  • Go to https://github.com/lionheart/bottlenose.

  • On the top right of the table listing out the files, you'll find the "Clone or Download menu", click on it.

  • In there you'll find an option to download a zip file. Click on it and unzip the file, once the download finishes.

  • Open a command prompt window and navigate to the unzipped folder and type in python setup.py install

  • Next, from the cmd line go to the directory where you saved this notebook and type in jupyter notebook in the command line, to open ju[yter notebook. A browser window will open showing you the current directory tree. click on the file with .ipynb extension.

    And that's it. If the command line spits out all sorts of errors at you, shoot me an email at rajkiran.gaddati@assurant.com and I'll be happy to help.

    Getting Amazon Product Data

    Amazon has a plethora of valuable data that we can use for various business process optimizations. For example, we can collect product pricing and demand(with supply, Prime and trade-in eligibility as its proxies) data over time to create a pricing model for our refurbished devices. Another use case could be mining the reviews of our competitors' device protection plans and find out what draws customers toward them.

    There are two popular ways to mine data from Amazon-

    1. Web scraping
    2. Use Amazon's Product Advertising API

    Web scraping has no official limitations and it is easier to mine reviews through this method. But Amazon is known to alter it's product format frequently which would mean that we'll have to rewrite our code everytime this happens. The use of iframes too makes this process harder. And lastly Amazon is know to ban ips for life(permaban), if caught.

    The Product api on the other hand is easy to implement and there is a lot of support for it both from Amazon and the open source community. The limitations here are that Amazon limits the queries per hour to 2000 with an unknown per minute query rate limit. Since the purpose of this API is to drive customers to the Amazon website, the limit will be increased by 200 per hour for each dollar of sales made through our API key.

    Amazon Product Advertising API

    Getting the API

    The API registration can be found at https://affiliate-program.amazon.com/gp/advertising/api/detail/main.html<\a>

    After signing up, you'll be directed to a page as shown in the screen shot below-

    Click on the "join now for free" link on the banner at the top of the page. You'll be taken to another registration page.

    Image('./AssoReg.PNG')
    Out[5]:

    On the 3rd page, enter an associate ID for your application in the first field. You'll need to verify your mobile number on the next page. The other fields, though mandatory, are not important for approval by Amazon.

    Once this is finished, go to https://console.aws.amazon.com/iam for your API key details.

    Under Security Status, click on "Delete Your Root Access Keys" and then "Manage Security Credentials".

    On the next page, under "Access Keys (Access Key ID and Secret Access Key)" create a new Access key. You'll find your Access ID and your secret key on the dialog box that appears. Note these down. These along with the Associate ID are needed for authenticating our page requests.

    Bottlenose

    There are many implementations of wrappers for the Amazon API for Python. Bottlenose is one of these and it is highly recommended by its users.

    You can find it at https://github.com/lionheart/bottlenose

searchIndex="Electronics"
ns={'amy':'http://webservices.amazon.com/AWSECommerceService/2011-08-01'}

    The api offers many lookup options. The one that's of most use to us is the ItemSearch method. It helps us search the website using keywords. SKUs and UPCs are also allowed.

    Anatomy of the request

    amazon.ItemSearch(Keywords, SearchIndex,ResponseGroup,Region)

    Keywords is a string of the serch terms

    SearchIndex is the product category in which to search

    ResponseGroup is a list of the types of responses we want. Some examples include OfferListings- Contains all the offers for a product, ItemAttributes- Contains item attributes such as title, ASIN, etc, SalesRank- Contains the product's sales rank, OfferSummary- Contains a summary of all the offers

    Region-Contains the region

    In [8]:
    amazon = bn.Amazon(AMAZON_ACCESS_KEY, AMAZON_SECRET_KEY,AMAZON_ASSOC_TAG, Region='US', MaxQPS=0.5, Timeout=5.0)
response = amazon.ItemSearch(Keywords=keywords,Region='US', SearchIndex=searchIndex,ResponseGroup='OfferListings,ItemAttributes,SalesRank,OfferSummary',ItemPage=1)
root=ET.fromstring(response)
numberOfPages=int(root.findall("./amy:Items/amy:TotalPages",ns)[0].text)
numerOfResults=int(root.findall("./amy:Items/amy:TotalResults",ns)[0].text)

print 'numberOfPages:',numberOfPages
print 'numerOfResults:',numerOfResults

    In [9]:
    def coalesce(x):   ##Function to handle requests where certain keys are unavailable
    try:
        return str(x.text)
    except:
        return None

##Write file header
with open('./amazon.dmp','w') as f:
    f.write('Time|ASIN|Product|Brand|Condition|TradeInValue|LowestNewPrice|LowestUsedPrice|LowestRefurbPrice|Price|SalesRank|URL|TotalNew|TotalUsed|TotalRefurb|Prime\n')

##Parse XML response and append to file
with open('./amazon.dmp','a') as f:    
    for i in range(10):  #Can only go through 10 pages
        response = amazon.ItemSearch(Keywords=keywords, SearchIndex=searchIndex,ResponseGroup='OfferListings,ItemAttributes,SalesRank,OfferSummary',ItemPage=i+1)
        root=ET.fromstring(response)
        
        #XPath is used to find keys in the XML response
        for i in root.findall('./amy:Items/amy:Item',ns):
            asin=coalesce(i.find('./amy:ASIN',ns))
            product=coalesce(i.find('./amy:ItemAttributes/amy:Title',ns))
            brand=coalesce(i.find('./amy:ItemAttributes/amy:Brand',ns))
            tradeInValue=coalesce(i.find('./amy:ItemAttributes/amy:TradeInValue',ns))

            salesRank=coalesce(i.find('./amy:SalesRank',ns))
            lowestUsedPrice=coalesce(i.find('./amy:OfferSummary/amy:LowestUsedPrice/amy:Amount',ns))
            lowestRefurbPrice=coalesce(i.find('./amy:OfferSummary/amy:LowestRefurbishedPrice/amy:Amount',ns))
            lowestNewPrice=coalesce(i.find('./amy:OfferSummary/amy:LowestNewPrice/amy:Amount',ns))
            totalUsed=coalesce(i.find('./amy:OfferSummary/amy:TotalUsed',ns))
            totalRefurbished=coalesce(i.find('./amy:OfferSummary/amy:TotalRefurbished',ns))
            totalNew=coalesce(i.find('./amy:OfferSummary/amy:TotalNew',ns))
            url=coalesce(i.find('./amy:DetailPageURL',ns))

            condition=coalesce(i.find('./amy:Offers/amy:Offer/amy:OfferAttributes/amy:Condition',ns))
            price=coalesce(i.find('./amy:Offers/amy:Offer/amy:OfferListing/amy:Price/amy:Amount',ns))
            prime=coalesce(i.find('./amy:Offers/amy:Offer/amy:OfferListing/amy:IsEligibleForPrime',ns))
            
            
            
            out=str(time)+'|'+str(asin)+'|'+str(product)+'|'+str(brand)+'|'+str(condition)+'|'+str(tradeInValue)+'|'+str(lowestNewPrice)+'|'+str(lowestUsedPrice)+'|'+str(lowestRefurbPrice)+'|'+str(price)+'|'+str(salesRank)+'|'+str(url)+'|'+str(totalNew)+'|'+str(totalUsed)+'|'+str(totalRefurbished)+'|'+str(prime)
            
            f.write(out+'\n')

    ##Write file header
with open('./amazon_reviews.dmp','w') as f:
    f.write('Time|ASIN|ReviewURL\n')

##Parse XML response and append to file
with open('./amazon_reviews.dmp','a') as f:    
    for i in range(10):
        response = amazon.ItemSearch(Keywords=keywords, SearchIndex=searchIndex,ResponseGroup='Reviews',ItemPage=i+1)
        root=ET.fromstring(response)
        
        #XPath is used to find keys in the XML response
        for i in root.findall('./amy:Items/amy:Item',ns):
            asin=coalesce(i.find('./amy:ASIN',ns))
            reviewUrl=ET.tostring(i.find('./amy:CustomerReviews/amy:IFrameURL',ns), method='text')
            
            out=str(time)+'|'+str(asin)+'|'+str(reviewUrl)
            
            f.write(out+'\n')

    In [16]:
    import re
from collections import Counter

with open('./stopWords.txt') as f:
    stopWords = f.read().splitlines()

stopWords=[i.upper() for i in stopWords]
reviews=[i.lower() for i in reviews]
    
mergedReviews=' '.join(reviews)

words = re.findall(r'\w+', mergedReviews)

cap_words = [word.upper() for word in words]

word_counts = Counter(cap_words)

df_words=pd.DataFrame(word_counts.items(), columns=['Word', 'Count'])

df_words=df_words[~df_words['Word'].isin(stopWords)]

df_words[df_words['Count']>10].sort_values('Count', ascending=False)

with open('./assurant_reviews.dmp','a') as f:    
    for i in range(10):
        response = amazon.ItemSearch(Keywords=keywords, SearchIndex=searchIndex,ResponseGroup='Reviews',ItemPage=i+1)
        root=ET.fromstring(response)
        
        #XPath is used to find keys in the XML response
        for i in root.findall('./amy:Items/amy:Item',ns):
            asin=coalesce(i.find('./amy:ASIN',ns))
            reviewUrl=ET.tostring(i.find('./amy:CustomerReviews/amy:IFrameURL',ns), method='text')
            
            out=str(time)+'|'+str(asin)+'|'+str(reviewUrl)
            
            f.write(out+'\n')

##Parse XML response and append to file
with open('./otherGuy_reviews.dmp','a') as f:    
    for i in range(10):
        response = amazon.ItemSearch(Keywords=keywords, SearchIndex=searchIndex,ResponseGroup='Reviews',ItemPage=i+1)
        root=ET.fromstring(response)
        
        #XPath is used to find keys in the XML response
        for i in root.findall('./amy:Items/amy:Item',ns):
            asin=coalesce(i.find('./amy:ASIN',ns))
            reviewUrl=ET.tostring(i.find('./amy:CustomerReviews/amy:IFrameURL',ns), method='text')
            
            out=str(time)+'|'+str(asin)+'|'+str(reviewUrl)
            
            f.write(out+'\n')
